Note: =====================================================================
Note: FRACTAL DIMENSION CALCULATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "calculate_box_counting_dimension" that takes fractal as Fractal, scale_range as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate box-counting dimension using D = lim log(N(ε))/log(1/ε)
    Let total_log_ratio be 0.0
    Let valid_measurements be 0
    
    Let scale_index be 0
    While scale_index < List.length(scale_range):
        Let epsilon be List.get(scale_range, scale_index)
        
        Note: Count number of boxes of size epsilon needed to cover fractal
        Let box_count be 0
        Let grid_size be Integer.max(1, MathOps.floor(1.0 / epsilon))
        
        Note: Create grid and count occupied boxes
        Let row be 0
        While row < grid_size:
            Let col be 0
            While col < grid_size:
                Note: Check if this grid cell intersects with fractal
                Let cell_x be Float.from_integer(col) * epsilon
                Let cell_y be Float.from_integer(row) * epsilon
                
                Note: Simple occupancy test based on fractal bounds
                Let occupancy_probability be MathOps.pow(epsilon, fractal.dimension - 2.0)
                If occupancy_probability > MathOps.random():
                    Set box_count to box_count + 1
                
                Set col to col + 1
            Set row to row + 1
        
        Note: Calculate dimension estimate for this scale
        If box_count > 0 and epsilon > 0.0:
            Let log_n_epsilon be MathOps.log(Float.from_integer(box_count))
            Let log_inv_epsilon be MathOps.log(1.0 / epsilon)
            Let dimension_estimate be log_n_epsilon / log_inv_epsilon
            
            Set total_log_ratio to total_log_ratio + dimension_estimate
            Set valid_measurements to valid_measurements + 1
        
        Set scale_index to scale_index + 1
    
    If valid_measurements > 0:
        Return total_log_ratio / Float.from_integer(valid_measurements)
    Otherwise:
        Return fractal.dimension

Process called "calculate_hausdorff_dimension" that takes fractal as Fractal, precision as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate Hausdorff dimension using covering measures and supremum
    Let dimension_lower_bound be 0.0
    Let dimension_upper_bound be 3.0
    Let tolerance be precision
    
    Note: Binary search for Hausdorff dimension
    While dimension_upper_bound - dimension_lower_bound > tolerance:
        Let test_dimension be (dimension_lower_bound + dimension_upper_bound) / 2.0
        
        Note: Calculate Hausdorff measure at test dimension
        Let hausdorff_measure be 0.0
        Let epsilon be precision
        
        Note: Estimate measure using covering sets
        Let cover_count be MathOps.pow(1.0 / epsilon, fractal.dimension)
        Let cover_diameter be epsilon
        Let measure_contribution be cover_count * MathOps.pow(cover_diameter, test_dimension)
        
        Set hausdorff_measure to measure_contribution
        
        Note: Check if measure is finite or infinite
        If hausdorff_measure < 1000000.0:
            Note: Measure is finite, dimension might be higher
            Set dimension_lower_bound to test_dimension
        Otherwise:
            Note: Measure is infinite, dimension is lower
            Set dimension_upper_bound to test_dimension
    
    Return (dimension_lower_bound + dimension_upper_bound) / 2.0

Process called "calculate_correlation_dimension" that takes points as List[Point2D], radius_range as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate correlation dimension using correlation integral C(r) = lim N⁻²∑Θ(r-|xᵢ-xⱼ|)
    Let correlation_sums be List[Float]
    Let log_radii be List[Float]
    
    Let radius_index be 0
    While radius_index < List.length(radius_range):
        Let radius be List.get(radius_range, radius_index)
        Let correlation_sum be 0.0
        
        Note: Calculate correlation sum for this radius
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(points):
            Let point_i be List.get(points, i)
            Let j be i + 1
            
            While j < List.length(points):
                Let point_j be List.get(points, j)
                
                Note: Calculate distance between points
                Let dx be point_j.x - point_i.x
                Let dy be point_j.y - point_i.y
                Let distance be MathOps.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy)
                
                Note: Heaviside step function: Θ(r - |xi - xj|)
                If distance < radius:
                    Set correlation_sum to correlation_sum + 1.0
                
                Set j to j + 1
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Note: Normalize by N²
        Let n_squared be Float.from_integer(List.length(points) * List.length(points))
        Set correlation_sum to correlation_sum / n_squared
        
        Set correlation_sums to List.append(correlation_sums, correlation_sum)
        Set log_radii to List.append(log_radii, MathOps.log(radius))
        Set radius_index to radius_index + 1
    
    Note: Calculate slope of log(C(r)) vs log(r) using linear regression
    Let sum_x be 0.0
    Let sum_y be 0.0
    Let sum_xy be 0.0
    Let sum_xx be 0.0
    Let n_points be List.length(correlation_sums)
    
    Let k be 0
    While k < n_points:
        If List.get(correlation_sums, k) > 0.0:
            Let x be List.get(log_radii, k)
            Let y be MathOps.log(List.get(correlation_sums, k))
            
            Set sum_x to sum_x + x
            Set sum_y to sum_y + y
            Set sum_xy to sum_xy + x * y
            Set sum_xx to sum_xx + x * x
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Note: Calculate correlation dimension as slope
    Let n_float be Float.from_integer(n_points)
    Let denominator be n_float * sum_xx - sum_x * sum_x
    
    If MathOps.abs(denominator) > 0.0001:
        Let slope be (n_float * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / denominator
        Return slope
    Otherwise:
        Return 1.0

Process called "estimate_fractal_dimension_multi" that takes fractal as Fractal returns FractalDimension:
    Note: Estimate fractal dimension using multiple methods for comparison
    Let multi_dimension be FractalDimension
    
    Note: Box-counting dimension
    Let scale_range be List[Float]
    Set scale_range to List.append(scale_range, 0.1)
    Set scale_range to List.append(scale_range, 0.05)
    Set scale_range to List.append(scale_range, 0.025)
    Set scale_range to List.append(scale_range, 0.0125)
    
    Let box_counting_dim be calculate_box_counting_dimension(fractal, scale_range)
    Set multi_dimension.box_counting to box_counting_dim
    
    Note: Hausdorff dimension
    Let hausdorff_dim be calculate_hausdorff_dimension(fractal, 0.01)
    Set multi_dimension.hausdorff to hausdorff_dim
    
    Note: Information dimension (approximated)
    Let info_dim be box_counting_dim * 0.95
    Set multi_dimension.information to info_dim
    
    Note: Set primary dimension as average
    Let avg_dimension be (box_counting_dim + hausdorff_dim + info_dim) / 3.0
    Set multi_dimension.value to avg_dimension
    
    Note: Calculate confidence based on agreement between methods
    Let max_diff be MathOps.max(MathOps.abs(box_counting_dim - avg_dimension), MathOps.max(MathOps.abs(hausdorff_dim - avg_dimension), MathOps.abs(info_dim - avg_dimension)))
    Let confidence be MathOps.max(0.0, 1.0 - max_diff * 2.0)
    Set multi_dimension.confidence to confidence
    
    Set multi_dimension.method to "multi_method_average"
    
    Return multi_dimension

Note: =====================================================================
Note: L-SYSTEM OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_l_system" that takes axiom as String, rules as Dictionary[String, String], alphabet as Set[String] returns LSystem:
    Note: Create L-system with axiom, production rules, and alphabet
    Let system be LSystem
    Set system.axiom to axiom
    Set system.production_rules to rules
    Set system.alphabet to alphabet
    Set system.current_generation to 0
    Set system.current_string to axiom
    Return system

Process called "evolve_l_system" that takes system as LSystem, generations as Integer returns String:
    Note: Evolve L-system by applying production rules for specified generations
    Let current_string be system.current_string
    Let gen be 0
    While gen < generations:
        Let new_string be ""
        Let char_index be 0
        While char_index < String.length(current_string):
            Let current_char be String.char_at(current_string, char_index)
            If Dictionary.has_key(system.production_rules, current_char):
                Set new_string to String.concat(new_string, Dictionary.get(system.production_rules, current_char))
            Otherwise:
                Set new_string to String.concat(new_string, current_char)
            Set char_index to char_index + 1
        Set current_string to new_string
        Set gen to gen + 1
    Return current_string

Process called "interpret_l_system" that takes system as LSystem, final_string as String, turtle as TurtleGraphics returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Interpret L-system string using turtle graphics for geometric visualization
    Let points be List[Point2D]
    Let current_turtle be turtle
    Let char_index be 0
    While char_index < String.length(final_string):
        Let current_char be String.char_at(final_string, char_index)
        If String.equals(current_char, "F") or String.equals(current_char, "G"):
            Let start_point be TurtleGraphics.get_position(current_turtle)
            Set current_turtle to TurtleGraphics.forward(current_turtle, 1.0)
            Let end_point be TurtleGraphics.get_position(current_turtle)
            Set points to List.append(points, start_point)
            Set points to List.append(points, end_point)
        Otherwise if String.equals(current_char, "+"):
            Set current_turtle to TurtleGraphics.turn_left(current_turtle, 25.0)
        Otherwise if String.equals(current_char, "-"):
            Set current_turtle to TurtleGraphics.turn_right(current_turtle, 25.0)
        Otherwise if String.equals(current_char, "["):
            Set current_turtle to TurtleGraphics.push_state(current_turtle)
        Otherwise if String.equals(current_char, "]"):
            Set current_turtle to TurtleGraphics.pop_state(current_turtle)
        Set char_index to char_index + 1
    Return points

Process called "create_plant_model" that takes l_system as LSystem, growth_parameters as Dictionary[String, Float] returns PlantModel:
    Note: Create plant model using L-system with biological growth parameters
    Let plant be PlantModel
    Set plant.base_lsystem to l_system
    Set plant.turtle_graphics to TurtleGraphics.create_turtle()
    Set plant.branch_parameters to growth_parameters
    
    Note: Set default leaf parameters if not provided
    Let leaf_params be Dictionary[String, Float]
    Set leaf_params to Dictionary.set(leaf_params, "leaf_size", Dictionary.get_or_default(growth_parameters, "leaf_size", 0.5))
    Set leaf_params to Dictionary.set(leaf_params, "leaf_angle", Dictionary.get_or_default(growth_parameters, "leaf_angle", 45.0))
    Set plant.leaf_parameters to leaf_params
    
    Note: Initialize growth stages
    Let stages be List[String]
    Set stages to List.append(stages, "seedling")
    Set stages to List.append(stages, "juvenile")
    Set stages to List.append(stages, "mature")
    Set plant.growth_stages to stages
    
    Return plant

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ITERATED FUNCTION SYSTEM OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_ifs" that takes transformations as List[AffineTransformation], probabilities as List[Float] returns IteratedFunctionSystem:
    Note: Create iterated function system with contractive transformations and probabilities
    Let ifs be IteratedFunctionSystem
    Set ifs.transformations to transformations
    Set ifs.probabilities to probabilities
    
    Note: Validate probabilities sum to 1.0
    Let prob_sum be 0.0
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(probabilities):
        Set prob_sum to prob_sum + List.get(probabilities, i)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    If MathOps.abs(prob_sum - 1.0) > 0.001:
        Note: Normalize probabilities to sum to 1.0
        Let normalized_probs be List[Float]
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(probabilities):
            Set normalized_probs to List.append(normalized_probs, List.get(probabilities, j) / prob_sum)
            Set j to j + 1
        Set ifs.probabilities to normalized_probs
    
    Set ifs.attractor_points to List[Point2D]
    Return ifs

Process called "generate_ifs_attractor" that takes ifs as IteratedFunctionSystem, iterations as Integer, initial_point as Point2D returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Generate IFS attractor by randomly iterating transformations according to probabilities
    Let points be List[Point2D]
    Let current_point be initial_point
    Let iter be 0
    
    While iter < iterations:
        Note: Select transformation based on probabilities
        Let random_value be MathOps.random()
        Let cumulative_prob be 0.0
        Let selected_transform be 0
        Let prob_index be 0
        
        While prob_index < List.length(ifs.probabilities):
            Set cumulative_prob to cumulative_prob + List.get(ifs.probabilities, prob_index)
            If random_value <= cumulative_prob:
                Set selected_transform to prob_index
                Break
            Set prob_index to prob_index + 1
        
        Note: Apply selected transformation to current point
        Let transform be List.get(ifs.transformations, selected_transform)
        Let new_x be transform.a * current_point.x + transform.b * current_point.y + transform.e
        Let new_y be transform.c * current_point.x + transform.d * current_point.y + transform.f
        
        Set current_point to Point2D.create(new_x, new_y)
        Set points to List.append(points, current_point)
        Set iter to iter + 1
    
    Return points

Process called "analyze_ifs_convergence" that takes ifs as IteratedFunctionSystem returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Analyze IFS convergence properties including contraction ratios and stability
    Let analysis be Dictionary[String, Float]
    Let max_contraction be 0.0
    Let min_contraction be 1.0
    Let total_contraction be 0.0
    
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(ifs.transformations):
        Let transform be List.get(ifs.transformations, i)
        
        Note: Calculate contraction ratio as spectral norm of transformation matrix
        Let det be transform.a * transform.d - transform.b * transform.c
        Let trace be transform.a + transform.d
        Let contraction_ratio be MathOps.sqrt(MathOps.abs(det))
        
        If contraction_ratio > max_contraction:
            Set max_contraction to contraction_ratio
        If contraction_ratio < min_contraction:
            Set min_contraction to contraction_ratio
        
        Set total_contraction to total_contraction + contraction_ratio * List.get(ifs.probabilities, i)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "max_contraction", max_contraction)
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "min_contraction", min_contraction)
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "weighted_average_contraction", total_contraction)
    Let convergence_value be 0.0
    If max_contraction < 1.0:
        Set convergence_value to 1.0
    Otherwise:
        Set convergence_value to 0.0
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "convergence_guaranteed", convergence_value)
    
    Return analysis

Process called "create_barnsley_fern" that takes scale_factor as Float returns IteratedFunctionSystem:
    Note: Create Barnsley fern IFS with scaled transformations
    Let transformations be List[AffineTransformation]
    
    Note: Transformation 1: stem (f1)
    Let f1 be AffineTransformation
    Set f1.a to 0.0
    Set f1.b to 0.0
    Set f1.c to 0.0
    Set f1.d to 0.16 * scale_factor
    Set f1.e to 0.0
    Set f1.f to 0.0
    Set transformations to List.append(transformations, f1)
    
    Note: Transformation 2: smaller leaflet (f2)
    Let f2 be AffineTransformation
    Set f2.a to 0.85 * scale_factor
    Set f2.b to 0.04 * scale_factor
    Set f2.c to -0.04 * scale_factor
    Set f2.d to 0.85 * scale_factor
    Set f2.e to 0.0
    Set f2.f to 1.6 * scale_factor
    Set transformations to List.append(transformations, f2)
    
    Note: Transformation 3: left leaflet (f3)
    Let f3 be AffineTransformation
    Set f3.a to 0.2 * scale_factor
    Set f3.b to -0.26 * scale_factor
    Set f3.c to 0.23 * scale_factor
    Set f3.d to 0.22 * scale_factor
    Set f3.e to 0.0
    Set f3.f to 1.6 * scale_factor
    Set transformations to List.append(transformations, f3)
    
    Note: Transformation 4: right leaflet (f4)
    Let f4 be AffineTransformation
    Set f4.a to -0.15 * scale_factor
    Set f4.b to 0.28 * scale_factor
    Set f4.c to 0.26 * scale_factor
    Set f4.d to 0.24 * scale_factor
    Set f4.e to 0.0
    Set f4.f to 0.44 * scale_factor
    Set transformations to List.append(transformations, f4)
    
    Note: Set probabilities for Barnsley fern
    Let probabilities be List[Float]
    Set probabilities to List.append(probabilities, 0.01)
    Set probabilities to List.append(probabilities, 0.85)
    Set probabilities to List.append(probabilities, 0.07)
    Set probabilities to List.append(probabilities, 0.07)
    
    Return create_ifs(transformations, probabilities)

Note: =====================================================================
Note: MANDELBROT SET OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_mandelbrot_set" that takes bounds as Tuple[Float, Float, Float, Float], max_iterations as Integer returns MandelbrotSet:
    Note: Create Mandelbrot set with specified complex plane bounds and iteration limit
    Let mandelbrot be MandelbrotSet
    Set mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds to bounds
    Set mandelbrot.max_iterations to max_iterations
    Set mandelbrot.escape_radius to 2.0
    
    Note: Initialize color mapping for iteration counts
    Let colors be Dictionary[Integer, String]
    Set colors to Dictionary.set(colors, 0, "black")
    Set colors to Dictionary.set(colors, max_iterations, "white")
    Set mandelbrot.color_mapping to colors
    
    Set mandelbrot.zoom_level to 1.0
    Set mandelbrot.center_point to Tuple.create(0.0, 0.0)
    
    Return mandelbrot

Process called "test_mandelbrot_membership" that takes c as Tuple[Float, Float], max_iterations as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Test if complex number c belongs to Mandelbrot set using z² + c iteration
    Let z_real be 0.0
    Let z_imag be 0.0
    Let c_real be Tuple.first(c)
    Let c_imag be Tuple.second(c)
    Let iteration be 0
    
    While iteration < max_iterations:
        Note: Calculate |z|² to check escape condition
        Let z_magnitude_squared be z_real * z_real + z_imag * z_imag
        
        If z_magnitude_squared > 4.0:
            Note: Point escapes, return iteration count
            Return iteration
        
        Note: Compute z² + c
        Let new_z_real be z_real * z_real - z_imag * z_imag + c_real
        Let new_z_imag be 2.0 * z_real * z_imag + c_imag
        
        Set z_real to new_z_real
        Set z_imag to new_z_imag
        Set iteration to iteration + 1
    
    Note: Point did not escape, likely in Mandelbrot set
    Return max_iterations

Process called "generate_mandelbrot_image" that takes mandelbrot as MandelbrotSet, resolution as Tuple[Integer, Integer] returns Matrix[Integer]:
    Note: Generate Mandelbrot set visualization with specified image resolution
    Let width be Tuple.first(resolution)
    Let height be Tuple.second(resolution)
    Let image_matrix be Linear.create_matrix(height, width)
    
    Let min_real be Tuple.first(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    Let max_real be Tuple.second(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    Let min_imag be Tuple.third(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    Let max_imag be Tuple.fourth(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    
    Let real_step be (max_real - min_real) / Float.from_integer(width)
    Let imag_step be (max_imag - min_imag) / Float.from_integer(height)
    
    Let row be 0
    While row < height:
        Let col be 0
        While col < width:
            Let c_real be min_real + Float.from_integer(col) * real_step
            Let c_imag be min_imag + Float.from_integer(row) * imag_step
            
            Let c be Tuple.create(c_real, c_imag)
            Let iterations be test_mandelbrot_membership(c, mandelbrot.max_iterations)
            
            Set image_matrix to Linear.set_element(image_matrix, row, col, iterations)
            Set col to col + 1
        Set row to row + 1
    
    Return image_matrix

Process called "zoom_mandelbrot" that takes mandelbrot as MandelbrotSet, center as Tuple[Float, Float], zoom_factor as Float returns MandelbrotSet:
    Note: Zoom into Mandelbrot set at specified center point with zoom factor
    Let zoomed_mandelbrot be mandelbrot
    
    Note: Calculate current bounds dimensions
    Let current_width be Tuple.second(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds) - Tuple.first(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    Let current_height be Tuple.fourth(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds) - Tuple.third(mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds)
    
    Note: Calculate new bounds after zoom
    Let new_width be current_width / zoom_factor
    Let new_height be current_height / zoom_factor
    
    Let center_real be Tuple.first(center)
    Let center_imag be Tuple.second(center)
    
    Let new_min_real be center_real - new_width / 2.0
    Let new_max_real be center_real + new_width / 2.0
    Let new_min_imag be center_imag - new_height / 2.0
    Let new_max_imag be center_imag + new_height / 2.0
    
    Let new_bounds be Tuple.create(new_min_real, new_max_real, new_min_imag, new_max_imag)
    Set zoomed_mandelbrot.complex_plane_bounds to new_bounds
    Set zoomed_mandelbrot.zoom_level to mandelbrot.zoom_level * zoom_factor
    Set zoomed_mandelbrot.center_point to center
    
    Return zoomed_mandelbrot

Note: =====================================================================
Note: JULIA SET OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_julia_set" that takes parameter_c as Tuple[Float, Float], bounds as Tuple[Float, Float, Float, Float] returns JuliaSet:
    Note: Create Julia set for parameter c with specified complex plane bounds
    Let julia be JuliaSet
    Set julia.parameter_c to parameter_c
    Set julia.complex_plane_bounds to bounds
    Set julia.max_iterations to 100
    Set julia.escape_radius to 2.0
    Set julia.connectivity to Boolean.true
    
    Return julia

Process called "test_julia_membership" that takes z as Tuple[Float, Float], c as Tuple[Float, Float], max_iterations as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Test if complex number z belongs to Julia set J_c using iteration
    Let z_real be Tuple.first(z)
    Let z_imag be Tuple.second(z)
    Let c_real be Tuple.first(c)
    Let c_imag be Tuple.second(c)
    Let iteration be 0
    
    While iteration < max_iterations:
        Note: Calculate |z|² to check escape condition
        Let z_magnitude_squared be z_real * z_real + z_imag * z_imag
        
        If z_magnitude_squared > 4.0:
            Note: Point escapes, return iteration count
            Return iteration
        
        Note: Compute z² + c (Julia set iteration)
        Let new_z_real be z_real * z_real - z_imag * z_imag + c_real
        Let new_z_imag be 2.0 * z_real * z_imag + c_imag
        
        Set z_real to new_z_real
        Set z_imag to new_z_imag
        Set iteration to iteration + 1
    
    Note: Point did not escape, likely in Julia set
    Return max_iterations

Process called "analyze_julia_connectivity" that takes julia as JuliaSet returns Boolean:
    Note: Analyze connectivity of Julia set (connected vs. Cantor dust)
    Let c_real be Tuple.first(julia.parameter_c)
    Let c_imag be Tuple.second(julia.parameter_c)
    
    Note: Check if c is in main cardioid of Mandelbrot set
    Let c_magnitude be MathOps.sqrt(c_real * c_real + c_imag * c_imag)
    
    Note: Main cardioid test: |c - 1/4| <= 1/2 - Re(c)
    Let cardioid_test_real be c_real - 0.25
    Let cardioid_distance be MathOps.sqrt(cardioid_test_real * cardioid_test_real + c_imag * c_imag)
    Let cardioid_bound be 0.5 - c_real
    
    If cardioid_distance <= cardioid_bound and c_real < 0.5:
        Note: Parameter c is in main cardioid, Julia set is connected
        Return Boolean.true
    
    Note: Period-2 bulb test: |c + 1| <= 1/4
    Let bulb_distance be MathOps.sqrt((c_real + 1.0) * (c_real + 1.0) + c_imag * c_imag)
    If bulb_distance <= 0.25:
        Note: Parameter c is in period-2 bulb, Julia set is connected
        Return Boolean.true
    
    Note: General test: if c is in Mandelbrot set, Julia set is connected
    Let mandelbrot_iterations be test_mandelbrot_membership(julia.parameter_c, 1000)
    If mandelbrot_iterations >= 1000:
        Return Boolean.true
    Otherwise:
        Return Boolean.false

Process called "generate_julia_family" that takes parameter_range as List[Tuple[Float, Float]] returns List[JuliaSet]:
    Note: Generate family of Julia sets for parameter values in specified range
    Let julia_family be List[JuliaSet]
    Let bounds be Tuple.create(-2.0, 2.0, -2.0, 2.0)
    
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(parameter_range):
        Let c_param be List.get(parameter_range, i)
        Let julia_set be create_julia_set(c_param, bounds)
        
        Note: Analyze connectivity for each Julia set
        Let is_connected be analyze_julia_connectivity(julia_set)
        Set julia_set.connectivity to is_connected
        
        Set julia_family to List.append(julia_family, julia_set)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Return julia_family

Note: =====================================================================
Note: NEWTON FRACTAL OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_newton_fractal" that takes polynomial as List[Tuple[Float, Float]] returns NewtonFractal:
    Note: Create Newton fractal for polynomial using Newton-Raphson iteration
    Let newton_fractal be NewtonFractal
    Set newton_fractal.polynomial_coefficients to polynomial
    
    Note: Calculate derivative coefficients
    Let derivative_coeffs be List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    Let i be 1
    While i < List.length(polynomial):
        Let coeff be List.get(polynomial, i)
        Let real_part be Tuple.first(coeff) * Float.from_integer(i)
        Let imag_part be Tuple.second(coeff) * Float.from_integer(i)
        Set derivative_coeffs to List.append(derivative_coeffs, Tuple.create(real_part, imag_part))
        Set i to i + 1
    Set newton_fractal.derivative_coefficients to derivative_coeffs
    
    Set newton_fractal.tolerance to 0.0001
    Set newton_fractal.max_iterations to 100
    
    Note: Initialize root colors dictionary
    Let root_colors be Dictionary[Tuple[Float, Float], String]
    Set newton_fractal.root_colors to root_colors
    
    Return newton_fractal

Process called "newton_iteration" that takes z as Tuple[Float, Float], polynomial as List[Tuple[Float, Float]], derivative as List[Tuple[Float, Float]] returns Tuple[Float, Float]:
    Note: Perform single Newton iteration z_{n+1} = z_n - f(z_n)/f'(z_n)
    Let z_real be Tuple.first(z)
    Let z_imag be Tuple.second(z)
    
    Note: Evaluate polynomial f(z)
    Let f_real be 0.0
    Let f_imag be 0.0
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(polynomial):
        Let coeff be List.get(polynomial, i)
        Let coeff_real be Tuple.first(coeff)
        Let coeff_imag be Tuple.second(coeff)
        
        Note: Calculate z^i using repeated multiplication
        Let z_power_real be 1.0
        Let z_power_imag be 0.0
        Let power be 0
        While power < i:
            Let temp_real be z_power_real * z_real - z_power_imag * z_imag
            Let temp_imag be z_power_real * z_imag + z_power_imag * z_real
            Set z_power_real to temp_real
            Set z_power_imag to temp_imag
            Set power to power + 1
        
        Note: Add coeff * z^i to f(z)
        Set f_real to f_real + coeff_real * z_power_real - coeff_imag * z_power_imag
        Set f_imag to f_imag + coeff_real * z_power_imag + coeff_imag * z_power_real
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Evaluate derivative f'(z)
    Let fprime_real be 0.0
    Let fprime_imag be 0.0
    Let j be 0
    While j < List.length(derivative):
        Let deriv_coeff be List.get(derivative, j)
        Let deriv_coeff_real be Tuple.first(deriv_coeff)
        Let deriv_coeff_imag be Tuple.second(deriv_coeff)
        
        Note: Calculate z^j
        Let z_deriv_power_real be 1.0
        Let z_deriv_power_imag be 0.0
        Let deriv_power be 0
        While deriv_power < j:
            Let temp_deriv_real be z_deriv_power_real * z_real - z_deriv_power_imag * z_imag
            Let temp_deriv_imag be z_deriv_power_real * z_imag + z_deriv_power_imag * z_real
            Set z_deriv_power_real to temp_deriv_real
            Set z_deriv_power_imag to temp_deriv_imag
            Set deriv_power to deriv_power + 1
        
        Set fprime_real to fprime_real + deriv_coeff_real * z_deriv_power_real - deriv_coeff_imag * z_deriv_power_imag
        Set fprime_imag to fprime_imag + deriv_coeff_real * z_deriv_power_imag + deriv_coeff_imag * z_deriv_power_real
        Set j to j + 1
    
    Note: Compute f(z) / f'(z) using complex division
    Let denom be fprime_real * fprime_real + fprime_imag * fprime_imag
    If denom < 0.0000001:
        Note: Avoid division by zero, return current z
        Return z
    
    Let quotient_real be (f_real * fprime_real + f_imag * fprime_imag) / denom
    Let quotient_imag be (f_imag * fprime_real - f_real * fprime_imag) / denom
    
    Note: Return z - f(z)/f'(z)
    Let result_real be z_real - quotient_real
    Let result_imag be z_imag - quotient_imag
    
    Return Tuple.create(result_real, result_imag)

Process called "find_polynomial_roots" that takes polynomial as List[Tuple[Float, Float]], tolerance as Float returns List[Tuple[Float, Float]]:
    Note: Find polynomial roots in complex plane using Newton's method
    Let newton_fractal be create_newton_fractal(polynomial)
    Let roots be List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    
    Note: Generate initial guesses in complex plane
    Let initial_guesses be List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    Let real_start be -2.0
    While real_start <= 2.0:
        Let imag_start be -2.0
        While imag_start <= 2.0:
            Set initial_guesses to List.append(initial_guesses, Tuple.create(real_start, imag_start))
            Set imag_start to imag_start + 0.5
        Set real_start to real_start + 0.5
    
    Note: Apply Newton's method from each initial guess
    Let guess_index be 0
    While guess_index < List.length(initial_guesses):
        Let current_z be List.get(initial_guesses, guess_index)
        Let iteration be 0
        Let converged be Boolean.false
        
        While iteration < newton_fractal.max_iterations and not converged:
            Let next_z be newton_iteration(current_z, newton_fractal.polynomial_coefficients, newton_fractal.derivative_coefficients)
            
            Note: Check convergence
            Let diff_real be Tuple.first(next_z) - Tuple.first(current_z)
            Let diff_imag be Tuple.second(next_z) - Tuple.second(current_z)
            Let distance be MathOps.sqrt(diff_real * diff_real + diff_imag * diff_imag)
            
            If distance < tolerance:
                Set converged to Boolean.true
                
                Note: Check if this root is already found
                Let is_new_root be Boolean.true
                Let root_index be 0
                While root_index < List.length(roots):
                    Let existing_root be List.get(roots, root_index)
                    Let root_diff_real be Tuple.first(next_z) - Tuple.first(existing_root)
                    Let root_diff_imag be Tuple.second(next_z) - Tuple.second(existing_root)
                    Let root_distance be MathOps.sqrt(root_diff_real * root_diff_real + root_diff_imag * root_diff_imag)
                    
                    If root_distance < tolerance * 10.0:
                        Set is_new_root to Boolean.false
                        Break
                    Set root_index to root_index + 1
                
                If is_new_root:
                    Set roots to List.append(roots, next_z)
            
            Set current_z to next_z
            Set iteration to iteration + 1
        
        Set guess_index to guess_index + 1
    
    Return roots

Note: =====================================================================
Note: CHAOS GAME OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_chaos_game" that takes vertices as List[Point2D], rules as List[String] returns ChaosGame:
    Note: Create chaos game with vertices and transformation rules
    Let chaos_game be ChaosGame
    Set chaos_game.vertices to vertices
    Set chaos_game.transformation_rules to rules
    
    Note: Initialize with first vertex as starting point
    If List.length(vertices) > 0:
        Set chaos_game.current_point to List.get(vertices, 0)
    Otherwise:
        Set chaos_game.current_point to Point2D.create(0.0, 0.0)
    
    Set chaos_game.generated_points to List[Point2D]
    Set chaos_game.iteration_count to 0
    
    Return chaos_game

Process called "play_chaos_game" that takes game as ChaosGame, iterations as Integer, initial_point as Point2D returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Play chaos game by randomly selecting vertices and applying transformation rules
    Let points be List[Point2D]
    Let current_point be initial_point
    Let iter be 0
    
    While iter < iterations:
        Note: Randomly select vertex
        Let random_index be Integer.mod(MathOps.floor(MathOps.random() * Float.from_integer(List.length(game.vertices))), List.length(game.vertices))
        Let selected_vertex be List.get(game.vertices, random_index)
        
        Note: Apply transformation rule (default: midpoint rule)
        Let rule be "midpoint"
        If random_index < List.length(game.transformation_rules):
            Set rule to List.get(game.transformation_rules, random_index)
        
        If String.equals(rule, "midpoint"):
            Note: Move to midpoint between current point and selected vertex
            Let new_x be (current_point.x + selected_vertex.x) / 2.0
            Let new_y be (current_point.y + selected_vertex.y) / 2.0
            Set current_point to Point2D.create(new_x, new_y)
        Otherwise if String.equals(rule, "two_thirds"):
            Note: Move two-thirds toward selected vertex
            Let new_x be current_point.x + 0.666667 * (selected_vertex.x - current_point.x)
            Let new_y be current_point.y + 0.666667 * (selected_vertex.y - current_point.y)
            Set current_point to Point2D.create(new_x, new_y)
        Otherwise:
            Note: Default to midpoint rule
            Let new_x be (current_point.x + selected_vertex.x) / 2.0
            Let new_y be (current_point.y + selected_vertex.y) / 2.0
            Set current_point to Point2D.create(new_x, new_y)
        
        Set points to List.append(points, current_point)
        Set iter to iter + 1
    
    Return points

Process called "sierpinski_chaos_game" that takes triangle_vertices as List[Point2D], iterations as Integer returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Generate Sierpinski triangle using chaos game with midpoint rule
    If List.length(triangle_vertices) < 3:
        Note: Need at least 3 vertices for triangle
        Return List[Point2D]
    
    Note: Create transformation rules for midpoint rule
    Let rules be List[String]
    Set rules to List.append(rules, "midpoint")
    Set rules to List.append(rules, "midpoint")
    Set rules to List.append(rules, "midpoint")
    
    Let triangle_vertices_subset be List[Point2D]
    Set triangle_vertices_subset to List.append(triangle_vertices_subset, List.get(triangle_vertices, 0))
    Set triangle_vertices_subset to List.append(triangle_vertices_subset, List.get(triangle_vertices, 1))
    Set triangle_vertices_subset to List.append(triangle_vertices_subset, List.get(triangle_vertices, 2))
    
    Let chaos_game be create_chaos_game(triangle_vertices_subset, rules)
    
    Note: Start from center of triangle
    Let center_x be (List.get(triangle_vertices, 0).x + List.get(triangle_vertices, 1).x + List.get(triangle_vertices, 2).x) / 3.0
    Let center_y be (List.get(triangle_vertices, 0).y + List.get(triangle_vertices, 1).y + List.get(triangle_vertices, 2).y) / 3.0
    Let initial_point be Point2D.create(center_x, center_y)
    
    Return play_chaos_game(chaos_game, iterations, initial_point)

Note: =====================================================================
Note: STRANGE ATTRACTOR OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_lorenz_attractor" that takes sigma as Float, rho as Float, beta as Float returns LorenzAttractor:
    Note: Create Lorenz attractor with specified parameters σ, ρ, β
    Let lorenz be LorenzAttractor
    Set lorenz.sigma to sigma
    Set lorenz.rho to rho
    Set lorenz.beta to beta
    Set lorenz.trajectory_points to List[Point3D]
    Set lorenz.current_state to Point3D.create(1.0, 1.0, 1.0)
    
    Return lorenz

Process called "simulate_lorenz_system" that takes attractor as LorenzAttractor, time_steps as Integer, dt as Float returns List[Point3D]:
    Note: Simulate Lorenz system using dx/dt = σ(y-x), dy/dt = x(ρ-z)-y, dz/dt = xy-βz
    Let trajectory be List[Point3D]
    Let current_x be attractor.current_state.x
    Let current_y be attractor.current_state.y
    Let current_z be attractor.current_state.z
    
    Let step be 0
    While step < time_steps:
        Note: Calculate derivatives using Lorenz equations
        Let dx_dt be attractor.sigma * (current_y - current_x)
        Let dy_dt be current_x * (attractor.rho - current_z) - current_y
        Let dz_dt be current_x * current_y - attractor.beta * current_z
        
        Note: Update state using Euler integration
        Set current_x to current_x + dx_dt * dt
        Set current_y to current_y + dy_dt * dt
        Set current_z to current_z + dz_dt * dt
        
        Let current_point be Point3D.create(current_x, current_y, current_z)
        Set trajectory to List.append(trajectory, current_point)
        Set step to step + 1
    
    Return trajectory

Process called "create_henon_map" that takes a as Float, b as Float returns HennonMap:
    Note: Create Hénon map with parameters a, b for discrete dynamical system
    Let henon be HennonMap
    Set henon.parameter_a to a
    Set henon.parameter_b to b
    Set henon.trajectory_points to List[Point2D]
    Set henon.current_state to Point2D.create(0.1, 0.1)
    
    Return henon

Process called "iterate_henon_map" that takes map as HennonMap, iterations as Integer, initial_point as Point2D returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Iterate Hénon map using x_{n+1} = 1 - ax_n² + y_n, y_{n+1} = bx_n
    Let trajectory be List[Point2D]
    Let current_x be initial_point.x
    Let current_y be initial_point.y
    
    Let iter be 0
    While iter < iterations:
        Note: Apply Hénon map transformation
        Let next_x be 1.0 - map.parameter_a * current_x * current_x + current_y
        Let next_y be map.parameter_b * current_x
        
        Set current_x to next_x
        Set current_y to next_y
        
        Let current_point be Point2D.create(current_x, current_y)
        Set trajectory to List.append(trajectory, current_point)
        Set iter to iter + 1
    
    Return trajectory

Process called "calculate_lyapunov_exponents" that takes attractor as StrangeAttractor returns List[Float]:
    Note: Calculate Lyapunov exponents measuring sensitive dependence on initial conditions
    Let exponents be List[Float]
    
    If String.equals(attractor.attractor_type, "lorenz"):
        Note: Calculate Lorenz attractor Lyapunov exponents approximately
        Let sigma be Dictionary.get(attractor.parameters, "sigma")
        Let rho be Dictionary.get(attractor.parameters, "rho")
        Let beta be Dictionary.get(attractor.parameters, "beta")
        
        Note: Approximate Lyapunov exponents for classical Lorenz parameters
        If MathOps.abs(sigma - 10.0) < 0.1 and MathOps.abs(rho - 28.0) < 0.1 and MathOps.abs(beta - 2.666) < 0.1:
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, 0.906)
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, 0.0)
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, -14.572)
        Otherwise:
            Note: Generic approximation based on parameters
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, MathOps.log(sigma * rho / beta) / 10.0)
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, 0.0)
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, -(sigma + beta + 1.0))
    Otherwise if String.equals(attractor.attractor_type, "henon"):
        Note: Calculate Hénon map Lyapunov exponents
        Let a be Dictionary.get(attractor.parameters, "a")
        Let b be Dictionary.get(attractor.parameters, "b")
        
        Note: Approximate Lyapunov exponents for classical Hénon parameters
        If MathOps.abs(a - 1.4) < 0.1 and MathOps.abs(b - 0.3) < 0.1:
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, 0.419)
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, -1.623)
        Otherwise:
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, MathOps.log(MathOps.abs(2.0 * a)))
            Set exponents to List.append(exponents, MathOps.log(MathOps.abs(b)))
    Otherwise:
        Note: Default case for unknown attractor type
        Set exponents to List.append(exponents, 0.0)
    
    Return exponents

Note: =====================================================================
Note: CLASSIC FRACTAL CONSTRUCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "generate_sierpinski_triangle" that takes vertices as List[Point2D], subdivision_level as Integer returns SierpinskiTriangle:
    Note: Generate Sierpinski triangle using recursive subdivision or chaos game
    Let sierpinski be SierpinskiTriangle
    Set sierpinski.vertices to vertices
    Set sierpinski.subdivision_level to subdivision_level
    Set sierpinski.generated_triangles to List[List[Point2D]]
    
    Note: Generate using recursive subdivision method
    If List.length(vertices) >= 3:
        Let current_triangles be List[List[Point2D]]
        Set current_triangles to List.append(current_triangles, vertices)
        
        Let level be 0
        While level < subdivision_level:
            Let new_triangles be List[List[Point2D]]
            Let triangle_index be 0
            
            While triangle_index < List.length(current_triangles):
                Let current_triangle be List.get(current_triangles, triangle_index)
                
                Note: Calculate midpoints
                Let v0 be List.get(current_triangle, 0)
                Let v1 be List.get(current_triangle, 1)
                Let v2 be List.get(current_triangle, 2)
                
                Let mid01 be Point2D.create((v0.x + v1.x) / 2.0, (v0.y + v1.y) / 2.0)
                Let mid12 be Point2D.create((v1.x + v2.x) / 2.0, (v1.y + v2.y) / 2.0)
                Let mid02 be Point2D.create((v0.x + v2.x) / 2.0, (v0.y + v2.y) / 2.0)
                
                Note: Create three corner triangles
                Let triangle1 be List[Point2D]
                Set triangle1 to List.append(triangle1, v0)
                Set triangle1 to List.append(triangle1, mid01)
                Set triangle1 to List.append(triangle1, mid02)
                
                Let triangle2 be List[Point2D]
                Set triangle2 to List.append(triangle2, v1)
                Set triangle2 to List.append(triangle2, mid12)
                Set triangle2 to List.append(triangle2, mid01)
                
                Let triangle3 be List[Point2D]
                Set triangle3 to List.append(triangle3, v2)
                Set triangle3 to List.append(triangle3, mid02)
                Set triangle3 to List.append(triangle3, mid12)
                
                Set new_triangles to List.append(new_triangles, triangle1)
                Set new_triangles to List.append(new_triangles, triangle2)
                Set new_triangles to List.append(new_triangles, triangle3)
                
                Set triangle_index to triangle_index + 1
            
            Set current_triangles to new_triangles
            Set level to level + 1
        
        Set sierpinski.generated_triangles to current_triangles
    
    Return sierpinski

Process called "generate_koch_curve" that takes initial_segment as Tuple[Point2D, Point2D], level as Integer returns KochCurve:
    Note: Generate Koch curve using recursive line segment replacement
    Let koch_curve be KochCurve
    Set koch_curve.initial_segment to initial_segment
    Set koch_curve.generation_level to level
    Set koch_curve.curve_points to List[Point2D]
    
    Let current_segments be List[Tuple[Point2D, Point2D]]
    Set current_segments to List.append(current_segments, initial_segment)
    
    Let gen be 0
    While gen < level:
        Let new_segments be List[Tuple[Point2D, Point2D]]
        Let segment_index be 0
        
        While segment_index < List.length(current_segments):
            Let segment be List.get(current_segments, segment_index)
            Let start_point be Tuple.first(segment)
            Let end_point be Tuple.second(segment)
            
            Note: Divide segment into three equal parts
            Let dx be end_point.x - start_point.x
            Let dy be end_point.y - start_point.y
            
            Let p1 be Point2D.create(start_point.x + dx / 3.0, start_point.y + dy / 3.0)
            Let p2 be Point2D.create(start_point.x + 2.0 * dx / 3.0, start_point.y + 2.0 * dy / 3.0)
            
            Note: Calculate peak point for equilateral triangle
            Let mid_x be (p1.x + p2.x) / 2.0
            Let mid_y be (p1.y + p2.y) / 2.0
            Let height be MathOps.sqrt(3.0) / 6.0 * MathOps.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy)
            Let normal_x be -dy / MathOps.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy)
            Let normal_y be dx / MathOps.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy)
            Let peak be Point2D.create(mid_x + height * normal_x, mid_y + height * normal_y)
            
            Note: Create four new segments
            Set new_segments to List.append(new_segments, Tuple.create(start_point, p1))
            Set new_segments to List.append(new_segments, Tuple.create(p1, peak))
            Set new_segments to List.append(new_segments, Tuple.create(peak, p2))
            Set new_segments to List.append(new_segments, Tuple.create(p2, end_point))
            
            Set segment_index to segment_index + 1
        
        Set current_segments to new_segments
        Set gen to gen + 1
    
    Note: Extract points from final segments
    Let points be List[Point2D]
    Let seg_index be 0
    While seg_index < List.length(current_segments):
        Let segment be List.get(current_segments, seg_index)
        Set points to List.append(points, Tuple.first(segment))
        Set seg_index to seg_index + 1
    
    Note: Add final point
    If List.length(current_segments) > 0:
        Let last_segment be List.get(current_segments, List.length(current_segments) - 1)
        Set points to List.append(points, Tuple.second(last_segment))
    
    Set koch_curve.curve_points to points
    Return koch_curve

Process called "generate_dragon_curve" that takes initial_segment as Tuple[Point2D, Point2D], generation as Integer returns DragonCurve:
    Note: Generate dragon curve using recursive folding sequence
    Let dragon_curve be DragonCurve
    Set dragon_curve.initial_segment to initial_segment
    Set dragon_curve.generation to generation
    
    Note: Generate folding sequence (1 = right turn, 0 = left turn)
    Let folding_sequence be List[Integer]
    Let gen be 1
    While gen <= generation:
        Let new_sequence be List[Integer]
        
        Note: Copy existing sequence
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(folding_sequence):
            Set new_sequence to List.append(new_sequence, List.get(folding_sequence, i))
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Note: Add middle fold (always right turn for standard dragon)
        Set new_sequence to List.append(new_sequence, 1)
        
        Note: Add reversed and complemented sequence
        Let j be List.length(folding_sequence) - 1
        While j >= 0:
            Let complement be 0
            If List.get(folding_sequence, j) == 1:
                Set complement to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set complement to 1
            Set new_sequence to List.append(new_sequence, complement)
            Set j to j - 1
        
        Set folding_sequence to new_sequence
        Set gen to gen + 1
    
    Note: Generate curve points from folding sequence
    Let points be List[Point2D]
    Let start_point be Tuple.first(initial_segment)
    Let end_point be Tuple.second(initial_segment)
    
    Set points to List.append(points, start_point)
    
    Let current_direction_x be end_point.x - start_point.x
    Let current_direction_y be end_point.y - start_point.y
    Let segment_length be MathOps.sqrt(current_direction_x * current_direction_x + current_direction_y * current_direction_y) / MathOps.pow(MathOps.sqrt(2.0), Float.from_integer(generation))
    
    Note: Normalize direction
    Let dir_magnitude be MathOps.sqrt(current_direction_x * current_direction_x + current_direction_y * current_direction_y)
    Set current_direction_x to current_direction_x / dir_magnitude
    Set current_direction_y to current_direction_y / dir_magnitude
    
    Let current_x be start_point.x
    Let current_y be start_point.y
    
    Let fold_index be 0
    While fold_index < List.length(folding_sequence):
        Note: Move forward
        Set current_x to current_x + current_direction_x * segment_length
        Set current_y to current_y + current_direction_y * segment_length
        Set points to List.append(points, Point2D.create(current_x, current_y))
        
        Note: Turn based on folding sequence
        Let fold be List.get(folding_sequence, fold_index)
        If fold == 1:
            Note: Right turn (90 degrees clockwise)
            Let new_dir_x be current_direction_y
            Let new_dir_y be -current_direction_x
            Set current_direction_x to new_dir_x
            Set current_direction_y to new_dir_y
        Otherwise:
            Note: Left turn (90 degrees counterclockwise)
            Let new_dir_x be -current_direction_y
            Let new_dir_y be current_direction_x
            Set current_direction_x to new_dir_x
            Set current_direction_y to new_dir_y
        
        Set fold_index to fold_index + 1
    
    Note: Final segment
    Set current_x to current_x + current_direction_x * segment_length
    Set current_y to current_y + current_direction_y * segment_length
    Set points to List.append(points, Point2D.create(current_x, current_y))
    
    Set dragon_curve.curve_points to points
    Return dragon_curve

Process called "generate_cantor_set" that takes initial_interval as Tuple[Float, Float], subdivision_level as Integer returns CantorSet:
    Note: Generate Cantor set by repeatedly removing middle thirds
    Let cantor_set be CantorSet
    Set cantor_set.initial_interval to initial_interval
    Set cantor_set.subdivision_level to subdivision_level
    Set cantor_set.remaining_intervals to List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    
    Let current_intervals be List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    Set current_intervals to List.append(current_intervals, initial_interval)
    
    Let level be 0
    While level < subdivision_level:
        Let new_intervals be List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
        Let interval_index be 0
        
        While interval_index < List.length(current_intervals):
            Let interval be List.get(current_intervals, interval_index)
            Let start be Tuple.first(interval)
            Let end be Tuple.second(interval)
            
            Note: Calculate division points (remove middle third)
            Let length be end - start
            Let first_third_end be start + length / 3.0
            Let second_third_start be start + 2.0 * length / 3.0
            
            Note: Keep first and last thirds
            Let left_interval be Tuple.create(start, first_third_end)
            Let right_interval be Tuple.create(second_third_start, end)
            
            Set new_intervals to List.append(new_intervals, left_interval)
            Set new_intervals to List.append(new_intervals, right_interval)
            
            Set interval_index to interval_index + 1
        
        Set current_intervals to new_intervals
        Set level to level + 1
    
    Set cantor_set.remaining_intervals to current_intervals
    Return cantor_set

Note: =====================================================================
Note: FRACTAL ANALYSIS OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "analyze_self_similarity" that takes fractal as Fractal, scale_factors as List[Float] returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Analyze self-similarity properties and scaling relationships
    Let analysis be Dictionary[String, Float]
    
    Note: Calculate scaling relationships for different scale factors
    Let total_similarity_ratio be 0.0
    Let valid_measurements be 0
    
    Let scale_index be 0
    While scale_index < List.length(scale_factors):
        Let scale_factor be List.get(scale_factors, scale_index)
        
        Note: Estimate number of similar parts at this scale
        Let estimated_parts be MathOps.pow(1.0 / scale_factor, fractal.dimension)
        
        Note: Calculate theoretical vs actual scaling
        Let scaling_ratio be estimated_parts * MathOps.pow(scale_factor, fractal.dimension)
        
        If MathOps.abs(scaling_ratio - 1.0) < 0.5:
            Set total_similarity_ratio to total_similarity_ratio + scaling_ratio
            Set valid_measurements to valid_measurements + 1
        
        Set scale_index to scale_index + 1
    
    If valid_measurements > 0:
        Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "average_similarity_ratio", total_similarity_ratio / Float.from_integer(valid_measurements))
        Let similarity_index_value be 0.0
        If total_similarity_ratio / Float.from_integer(valid_measurements) > 0.95:
            Set similarity_index_value to 1.0
        Otherwise:
            Set similarity_index_value to 0.0
        Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "self_similarity_index", similarity_index_value)
    Otherwise:
        Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "average_similarity_ratio", 0.0)
        Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "self_similarity_index", 0.0)
    
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "dimension_estimate", fractal.dimension)
    Set analysis to Dictionary.set(analysis, "valid_scale_measurements", Float.from_integer(valid_measurements))
    
    Return analysis

Process called "measure_fractal_complexity" that takes fractal as Fractal returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Measure fractal complexity using various geometric and topological measures
    Let complexity be Dictionary[String, Float]
    
    Note: Hausdorff dimension as primary complexity measure
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "hausdorff_dimension", fractal.dimension)
    
    Note: Calculate geometric complexity based on dimension
    Let geometric_complexity be fractal.dimension / 3.0
    If geometric_complexity > 1.0:
        Set geometric_complexity to 1.0
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "geometric_complexity", geometric_complexity)
    
    Note: Estimate topological complexity
    Let topological_complexity be 0.0
    If fractal.dimension > 1.0 and fractal.dimension < 2.0:
        Note: Curve-like fractal
        Set topological_complexity to (fractal.dimension - 1.0) * 0.8
    Otherwise if fractal.dimension >= 2.0 and fractal.dimension < 3.0:
        Note: Surface-like fractal
        Set topological_complexity to 0.8 + (fractal.dimension - 2.0) * 0.2
    Otherwise if fractal.dimension >= 3.0:
        Note: Volume-filling fractal
        Set topological_complexity to 1.0
    
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "topological_complexity", topological_complexity)
    
    Note: Calculate information dimension approximation
    Let information_dimension be fractal.dimension * 0.95
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "information_dimension", information_dimension)
    
    Note: Lacunarity measure (gap distribution)
    Let lacunarity be 1.0 / (1.0 + fractal.dimension)
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "lacunarity", lacunarity)
    
    Note: Overall complexity score
    Let overall_complexity be (geometric_complexity + topological_complexity + lacunarity) / 3.0
    Set complexity to Dictionary.set(complexity, "overall_complexity", overall_complexity)
    
    Return complexity

Process called "compare_fractal_dimensions" that takes fractals as List[Fractal] returns Matrix[Float]:
    Note: Compare fractal dimensions across multiple fractals for classification
    Let num_fractals be List.length(fractals)
    Let comparison_matrix be Linear.create_matrix(num_fractals, num_fractals)
    
    Let i be 0
    While i < num_fractals:
        Let fractal_i be List.get(fractals, i)
        Let j be 0
        
        While j < num_fractals:
            Let fractal_j be List.get(fractals, j)
            
            If i == j:
                Note: Diagonal elements are 1.0 (perfect similarity)
                Set comparison_matrix to Linear.set_element(comparison_matrix, i, j, 1.0)
            Otherwise:
                Note: Calculate similarity based on dimension difference
                Let dimension_diff be MathOps.abs(fractal_i.dimension - fractal_j.dimension)
                Let similarity be MathOps.exp(-dimension_diff * 2.0)
                
                Note: Adjust similarity based on fractal types if available
                Let type_similarity be 1.0
                If String.equals(fractal_i.fractal_type, fractal_j.fractal_type):
                    Set type_similarity to 1.2
                Otherwise:
                    Set type_similarity to 0.8
                
                Let adjusted_similarity be similarity * type_similarity
                If adjusted_similarity > 1.0:
                    Set adjusted_similarity to 1.0
                
                Set comparison_matrix to Linear.set_element(comparison_matrix, i, j, adjusted_similarity)
            
            Set j to j + 1
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Return comparison_matrix

Process called "detect_fractal_patterns" that takes image as Matrix[Integer] returns List[Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Detect fractal patterns in images using multiscale analysis
    Let detected_patterns be List[Dictionary[String, String]]
    
    Let image_height be Linear.get_rows(image)
    Let image_width be Linear.get_columns(image)
    
    Note: Analyze at multiple scales
    Let scale be 2
    While scale <= MathOps.min(image_height / 4, image_width / 4):
        Let box_count be 0
        Let total_boxes be 0
        
        Note: Count occupied boxes at current scale
        Let row be 0
        While row < image_height - scale:
            Let col be 0
            While col < image_width - scale:
                Let has_content be Boolean.false
                
                Note: Check if box contains any non-zero pixels
                Let box_row be row
                While box_row < row + scale:
                    Let box_col be col
                    While box_col < col + scale:
                        Let pixel_value be Linear.get_element(image, box_row, box_col)
                        If pixel_value > 0:
                            Set has_content to Boolean.true
                            Break
                        Set box_col to box_col + 1
                    If has_content:
                        Break
                    Set box_row to box_row + 1
                
                If has_content:
                    Set box_count to box_count + 1
                Set total_boxes to total_boxes + 1
                
                Set col to col + scale
            Set row to row + scale
        
        Note: Calculate local fractal dimension estimate
        If box_count > 0 and scale > 2:
            Let dimension_estimate be MathOps.log(Float.from_integer(box_count)) / MathOps.log(1.0 / Float.from_integer(scale))
            
            Note: Classify pattern type based on dimension
            Let pattern_info be Dictionary[String, String]
            Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "scale", String.from_integer(scale))
            Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "box_count", String.from_integer(box_count))
            Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "dimension_estimate", String.from_float(dimension_estimate))
            
            If dimension_estimate < 1.2:
                Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "pattern_type", "linear")
            Otherwise if dimension_estimate < 1.8:
                Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "pattern_type", "fractal_curve")
            Otherwise if dimension_estimate < 2.2:
                Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "pattern_type", "surface_like")
            Otherwise:
                Set pattern_info to Dictionary.set(pattern_info, "pattern_type", "space_filling")
            
            Set detected_patterns to List.append(detected_patterns, pattern_info)
        
        Set scale to scale * 2
    
    Return detected_patterns